# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x-ray-diffraction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] In many areas of science, **Bragg's law** – also known as **Wulff–Bragg's condition** or **Laue–Bragg interference** – is a special case of Laue diffraction that gives the angles for coherent scattering of waves from a large crystal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] It describes how the superposition of wave fronts scattered by lattice planes leads to a strict relation between the wavelength and scattering angle.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] This law was initially formulated for X-rays, but it also applies to all types of matter waves including neutron and electron waves if there are a large number of atoms, as well as to visible light with artificial periodic microscale lattices.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] They found that these crystals, at certain specific wavelengths and incident angles, produced intense peaks of reflected radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Lawrence Bragg explained this result by modeling the crystal as a set of discrete parallel planes separated by a constant parameter d.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] He proposed that the incident X-ray radiation would produce a Bragg peak if reflections off the various planes interfered constructively.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The interference is constructive when the phase difference between the wave reflected off different atomic planes is a multiple of 2*π*; this condition (see *Bragg condition* section below) was first presented by Lawrence Bragg on 11 November 1912 to the Cambridge Philosophical Society.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Due to its simplicity, Bragg's law provided a powerful new tool for determining crystal lattices from X-ray diffraction data.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Lawrence Bragg and his father, William Henry Bragg, were awarded the Nobel Prize in physics in 1915 for their work in solving crystal structures beginning with NaCl, ZnS, and diamond.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] They are the only father-son team to jointly win.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The concept of Bragg diffraction applies equally to neutron diffraction and approximately to electron diffraction.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] In both cases the wavelengths are comparable with inter-atomic distances (~ 150 pm).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Many other types of matter waves have also been shown to diffract, and also light from objects with a larger ordered structure such as opals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Bragg diffraction occurs when radiation of a wavelength λ comparable to atomic spacings is scattered in a specular fashion (mirror-like reflection) by planes of atoms in a crystalline material, and undergoes constructive interference.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] When the scattered waves are incident at a specific angle, they remain in phase and constructively interfere.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] This equation, Bragg's law, describes the condition on *θ* for constructive interference.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] A map of the intensities of the scattered waves as a function of their angle is called a diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Strong intensities known as Bragg peaks are obtained in the diffraction pattern when the scattering angles satisfy Bragg condition.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] This is a special case of the more general Laue equations, and the Laue equations can be shown to reduce to the Bragg condition with additional assumptions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] In Bragg's original paper he describes his approach as a Huygens's construction for a reflected wave.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Suppose that a plane wave (of any type) is incident on planes of lattice points, with separation d , at an angle $\theta$ as shown in the Figure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Points **A** and **C** are on one plane, and **B** is on the plane below.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] There will be a path difference between the ray that gets reflected along **AC'** and the ray that gets transmitted along **AB**, then reflected along **BC**.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] where n and $\lambda$ are an integer and the wavelength of the incident wave respectively.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] which simplifies to $n\lambda =2d\sin \theta \,,$ which is Bragg's law shown above.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] If only two planes of atoms were diffracting, as shown in the Figure then the transition from constructive to destructive interference would be gradual as a function of angle, with gentle maxima at the Bragg angles.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] However, since many atomic planes are participating in most real materials, sharp peaks are typical.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] A rigorous derivation from the more general Laue equations is available (see page: Laue equations).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The Bragg condition is correct for very large crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Because the scattering of X-rays and neutrons is relatively weak, in many cases quite large crystals with sizes of 100 nm or more are used.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] While there can be additional effects due to crystal defects, these are often quite small.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] In contrast, electrons interact thousands of times more strongly with solids than X-rays, and also lose energy (inelastic scattering).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Therefore, samples used in transmission electron diffraction are much thinner.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Typical diffraction patterns, for instance the Figure, show spots for different directions (plane waves) of the electrons leaving a crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The angles that Bragg's law predicts are still approximately right, but in general there is a lattice of spots which are close to projections of the reciprocal lattice that is at right angles to the direction of the electron beam.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] (In contrast, Bragg's law predicts that only one or perhaps two would be present, not simultaneously tens to hundreds.) With low-energy electron diffraction where the electron energies are typically 30-1000 electron volts, the result is similar with the electrons reflected back from a surface.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Also similar is reflection high-energy electron diffraction which typically leads to rings of diffraction spots.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] With X-rays the effect of having small crystals is described by the Scherrer equation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] This leads to broadening of the Bragg peaks which can be used to estimate the size of the crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] A colloidal crystal is a highly ordered array of particles that forms over a long range (from a few millimeters to one centimeter in length); colloidal crystals have appearance and properties roughly analogous to their atomic or molecular counterparts.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Periodic arrays of spherical particles give rise to interstitial voids (the spaces between the particles), which act as a natural diffraction grating for visible light waves, when the interstitial spacing is of the same order of magnitude as the incident lightwave.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] In these cases brilliant iridescence (or play of colours) is attributed to the diffraction and constructive interference of visible lightwaves according to Bragg's law, in a matter analogous to the scattering of X-rays in crystalline solid.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The effects occur at visible wavelengths because the interplanar spacing d is much larger than for true crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Precious opal is one example of a colloidal crystal with optical effects.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Volume Bragg gratings (VBG) or volume holographic gratings (VHG) consist of a volume where there is a periodic change in the refractive index.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Depending on the orientation of the refractive index modulation, VBG can be used either to transmit or reflect a small bandwidth of wavelengths.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] where m is the Bragg order (a positive integer), *λ*B the diffracted wavelength, Λ the fringe spacing of the grating, θ the angle between the incident beam and the normal (**N**) of the entrance surface and φ the angle between the normal and the grating vector (**KG**).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Radiation that does not match Bragg's law will pass through the VBG undiffracted.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The output wavelength can be tuned over a few hundred nanometers by changing the incident angle (θ).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] VBG are being used to produce widely tunable laser source or perform global hyperspectral imagery (see Photon etc.).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] The measurement of the angles can be used to determine crystal structure, see x-ray crystallography for more details.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] where a is the lattice spacing of the cubic crystal, and h, k, and ℓ are the Miller indices of the Bragg plane.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] One can derive selection rules for the Miller indices for different cubic Bravais lattices as well as many others, a few of the selection rules are given in the table below.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] These selection rules can be used for any crystal with the given crystal structure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] KCl has a face-centered cubic Bravais lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] However, the K+ and the Cl− ion have the same number of electrons and are quite close in size, so that the diffraction pattern becomes essentially the same as for a simple cubic structure with half the lattice parameter.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Selection rules for other structures can be referenced elsewhere, or derived.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/bragg-s-law] Lattice spacing for the other crystal systems can be found here.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] A **diffractometer** is a measuring instrument for analyzing the structure of a material from the scattering pattern produced when a beam of radiation or particles (such as X-rays or neutrons) interacts with it.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] A typical diffractometer consists of a source of radiation, a monochromator to choose the wavelength, slits to adjust the shape of the beam, a sample and a detector.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] In a more complicated apparatus, a goniometer can also be used for fine adjustment of the sample and the detector positions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] When an area detector is used to monitor the diffracted radiation, a beamstop is usually needed to stop the intense primary beam that has not been diffracted by the sample, otherwise the detector might be damaged.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] Usually the beamstop can be completely impenetrable to the X-rays or it may be semitransparent.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] The use of a semitransparent beamstop allows the possibility to determine how much the sample absorbs the radiation using the intensity observed through the beamstop.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] There are several types of X-ray diffractometer, depending on the research field (material sciences, powder diffraction, life sciences, structural biology, etc.) and the experimental environment, if it is a laboratory with its home X-ray source or a Synchrotron.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] In laboratory, diffractometers are usually an "all in one" equipment, including the diffractometer, the video microscope and the X-ray source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] Plenty of companies manufacture "all in one" equipment for X-ray home laboratory, such as Rigaku, Malvern Panalytical, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Bruker, Anton Paar and many others.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] There are fewer diffractometer manufacturers for synchrotrons, owing to few numbers of x-ray beamlines to equip and the need of solid expertise of the manufacturer.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] For material sciences, Huber diffractometers are widely known and, for structural biology, Arinax diffractometers are the reference.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] Nonetheless, due to few numbers of manufacturers, a large amount of synchrotron diffractometers are "homemade" diffractometers, realized by synchrotron engineering teams.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] X-ray diffractometer instruments can be used for a variety of purposes including imaging crystal structures, phase determination, and identifying unfamiliar substances for use in crystallography, inspection, and pharmaceutical research for drug efficacy.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/diffractometer] A novel use of x-ray diffraction involves studying the surface of Mars to determine if it ever supported life.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder diffraction stands in contrast to single crystal diffraction techniques, which work best with a single, well-ordered crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The most common type of powder diffraction is with X-rays, the focus of this article, although some aspects of neutron powder diffraction are mentioned.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] (Powder electron diffraction is more complex due to dynamical diffraction and is not discussed further herein.) Typical diffractometers use electromagnetic radiation (waves) with known wavelength and frequency, which is determined by their source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The source is often X-rays, and neutrons are also common sources, with their frequency determined by their de Broglie wavelength.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] When these waves reach the sample, the incoming beam is either reflected off the surface, or can enter the lattice and be diffracted by the atoms present in the sample.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] If the atoms are arranged symmetrically with a separation distance *d*, these waves will interfere constructively only where the path-length difference 2*d* sin *θ* is equal to an integer multiple of the wavelength, producing a diffraction maximum in accordance with Bragg's law.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] These waves interfere destructively at points between the intersections where the waves are out of phase, and do not lead to bright spots in the diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Because the sample itself is acting as the diffraction grating, this spacing is the atomic spacing.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The distinction between powder and single crystal diffraction is the degree of texturing in the sample.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Single crystals have maximal texturing, and are said to be anisotropic.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In contrast, in powder diffraction, every possible crystalline orientation is represented equally in a powdered sample, the isotropic case.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) operates under the assumption that the sample is randomly arranged.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Therefore, a statistically significant number of each plane of the crystal structure will be in the proper orientation to diffract the X-rays.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Therefore, each plane will be represented in the signal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In practice, it is sometimes necessary to rotate the sample orientation to eliminate the effects of texturing and achieve true randomness.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Mathematically, crystals can be described by a Bravais lattice with some regularity in the spacing between atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Because of this regularity, we can describe this structure in a different way using the reciprocal lattice, which is related to the original structure by a Fourier transform.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This three-dimensional space can be described with reciprocal axes *x**, *y**, and *z** or alternatively in spherical coordinates *q*, *φ**, and *χ**.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In powder diffraction, intensity is homogeneous over *φ** and *χ**, and only *q* remains as an important measurable quantity.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This is because orientational averaging causes the three-dimensional reciprocal space that is studied in single crystal diffraction to be projected onto a single dimension.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] When the scattered radiation is collected on a flat plate detector, the rotational averaging leads to smooth diffraction rings around the beam axis, rather than the discrete Laue spots observed in single crystal diffraction.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The angle between the beam axis and the ring is called the *scattering angle* and in X-ray crystallography always denoted as 2*θ* (in scattering of *visible* light the convention is usually to call it *θ*).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In accordance with Bragg's law, each ring corresponds to a particular reciprocal lattice vector *G* in the sample crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In this equation, *G* is the reciprocal lattice vector, *q* is the length of the reciprocal lattice vector, *k* is the momentum transfer vector, *θ* is half of the scattering angle, and *λ* is the wavelength of the source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder diffraction data are usually presented as a diffractogram in which the diffracted intensity, *I*, is shown as a function either of the scattering angle 2*θ* or as a function of the scattering vector length *q*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The latter variable has the advantage that the diffractogram no longer depends on the value of the wavelength *λ*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The advent of synchrotron sources has widened the choice of wavelength considerably.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] To facilitate comparability of data obtained with different wavelengths the use of *q* is therefore recommended and gaining acceptability.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Relative to other methods of analysis, powder diffraction allows for rapid, non-destructive analysis of multi-component mixtures without the need for extensive sample preparation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This gives laboratories the ability to quickly analyze unknown materials and perform materials characterization in such fields as metallurgy, mineralogy, chemistry, forensic science, archeology, condensed matter physics, and the biological and pharmaceutical sciences.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Identification is performed by comparison of the diffraction pattern to a known standard or to a database such as the International Centre for Diffraction Data's Powder Diffraction File (PDF) or the Cambridge Structural Database (CSD).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Advances in hardware and software, particularly improved optics and fast detectors, have dramatically improved the analytical capability of the technique, especially relative to the speed of the analysis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The fundamental physics upon which the technique is based provides high precision and accuracy in the measurement of interplanar spacings, sometimes to fractions of an Ångström, resulting in authoritative identification frequently used in patents, criminal cases and other areas of law enforcement.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The ability to analyze multiphase materials also allows analysis of how materials interact in a particular matrix such as a pharmaceutical tablet, a circuit board, a mechanical weld, a geologic core sampling, cement and concrete, or a pigment found in an historic painting.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The method has been historically used for the identification and classification of minerals, but it can be used for nearly any material, even amorphous ones, so long as a suitable reference pattern is known or can be constructed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The most widespread use of powder diffraction is in the identification and characterization of crystalline solids, each of which produces a distinctive diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Both the positions (corresponding to lattice spacings) and the relative intensity of the lines in a diffraction pattern are indicative of a particular phase and material, providing a "fingerprint" for comparison.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A multi-phase mixture, e.g. a soil sample, will show more than one pattern superposed, allowing for the determination of the relative concentrations of phases in the mixture.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Hanawalt, an analytical chemist who worked for Dow Chemical in the 1930s, was the first to realize the analytical potential of creating a database.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Today it is represented by the Powder Diffraction File (PDF) of the International Centre for Diffraction Data (formerly Joint Committee for Powder Diffraction Studies).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This has been made searchable by computer through the work of global software developers and equipment manufacturers.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] There are now over 1,047,661 reference materials in the 2021 Powder Diffraction File Databases, and these databases are interfaced to a wide variety of diffraction analysis software and distributed globally.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The Powder Diffraction File contains many subfiles, such as minerals, metals and alloys, pharmaceuticals, forensics, excipients, superconductors, semiconductors, etc., with large collections of organic, organometallic and inorganic reference materials.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In contrast to a crystalline pattern consisting of a series of sharp peaks, amorphous materials (liquids, glasses etc.) produce a broad background signal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Many polymers show semicrystalline behavior, *i.e.* part of the material forms an ordered crystallite by folding of the molecule.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A single polymer molecule may well be folded into two different, adjacent crystallites and thus form a tie between the two.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The tie part is prevented from crystallizing.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The result is that the crystallinity will never reach 100%.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder XRD can be used to determine the crystallinity by comparing the integrated intensity of the background pattern to that of the sharp peaks.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Values obtained from powder XRD are typically comparable but not quite identical to those obtained from other methods such as DSC.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The position of a diffraction peak is independent of the atomic positions within the cell and entirely determined by the size and shape of the unit cell of the crystalline phase.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Each peak represents a certain lattice plane and can therefore be characterized by a Miller index.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] If the symmetry is high, e.g.: cubic or hexagonal it is usually not too hard to identify the index of each peak, even for an unknown phase.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This is particularly important in solid-state chemistry, where one is interested in finding and identifying new materials.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Once a pattern has been indexed, this characterizes the reaction product and identifies it as a new solid phase.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Indexing programs exist to deal with the harder cases, but if the unit cell is very large and the symmetry low (triclinic) success is not always guaranteed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Cell parameters are somewhat temperature and pressure dependent.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder diffraction can be combined with *in situ* temperature and pressure control.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] As these thermodynamic variables are changed, the observed diffraction peaks will migrate continuously to indicate higher or lower lattice spacings as the unit cell distorts.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This allows for measurement of such quantities as the thermal expansion tensor and the isothermal bulk modulus, as well determination of the full equation of state of the material.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] At some critical set of conditions, for example 0 °C for water at 1 atm, a new arrangement of atoms or molecules may become stable, leading to a phase transition.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] At this point new diffraction peaks will appear or old ones disappear according to the symmetry of the new phase.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] If the material melts to an isotropic liquid, all sharp lines will disappear and be replaced by a broad amorphous pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] If the transition produces another crystalline phase, one set of lines will suddenly be replaced by another set.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In some cases however lines will split or coalesce, e.g. if the material undergoes a continuous, second order phase transition.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In such cases the symmetry may change because the existing structure is *distorted* rather than replaced by a completely different one.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] For example, the diffraction peaks for the lattice planes (100) and (001) can be found at two different values of q for a tetragonal phase, but if the symmetry becomes cubic the two peaks will come to coincide.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Crystal structure determination from powder diffraction data is extremely challenging due to the overlap of reflections in a powder experiment.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A number of different methods exist for structural determination, such as simulated annealing and charge flipping.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The crystal structures of known materials can be refined, i.e. as a function of temperature or pressure, using the Rietveld method.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The Rietveld method is a so-called full pattern analysis technique.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A crystal structure, together with instrumental and microstructural information, is used to generate a theoretical diffraction pattern that can be compared to the observed data.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A least squares procedure is then used to minimize the difference between the calculated pattern and each point of the observed pattern by adjusting model parameters.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Techniques to determine unknown structures from powder data do exist, but are somewhat specialized.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A number of programs that can be used in structure determination are TOPAS, Fox, DASH, GSAS-II, EXPO2004, and a few others.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] As alternative to the Rietveld method, machine learning algorithms have been applied to crystals structure classification based on powder diffraction.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] There are many factors that determine the width B of a diffraction peak.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] It is often possible to separate the effects of size and strain.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] When size broadening is independent of q (K = 1/d), strain broadening increases with increasing q-values.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In most cases there will be both size and strain broadening.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Thus, when we plot $\displaystyle B\cdot \cos(\theta )$ vs. $\displaystyle \sin(\theta )$ we get a straight line with slope $\displaystyle \eta$ and intercept $\displaystyle {\frac {k\lambda }{D}}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The expression is a combination of the Scherrer equation for size broadening and the Stokes and Wilson expression for strain broadening.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The value of η is the strain in the crystallites, the value of D represents the size of the crystallites.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The constant *k* is typically close to unity and ranges from 0.8 to 1.39.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] X-ray photons scatter by interaction with the electron cloud of the material, neutrons are scattered by the nuclei.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This means that, in the presence of heavy atoms with many electrons, it may be difficult to detect light atoms by X-ray diffraction.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In contrast, the neutron scattering lengths of most atoms are approximately equal in magnitude.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Neutron diffraction techniques may therefore be used to detect light elements such as oxygen or hydrogen in combination with heavy atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The neutron diffraction technique therefore has obvious applications to problems such as determining oxygen displacements in materials like high temperature superconductors and ferroelectrics, or to hydrogen bonding in biological systems.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A further complication in the case of neutron scattering from hydrogenous materials is the strong incoherent scattering of hydrogen (80.27(6) barn).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This leads to a very high background in neutron diffraction experiments, and may make structural investigations impossible.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A common solution is deuteration, i.e., replacing the 1-H atoms in the sample with deuterium (2-H).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The incoherent scattering length of deuterium is much smaller (2.05(3) barn) making structural investigations significantly easier.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] However, in some systems, replacing hydrogen with deuterium may alter the structural and dynamic properties of interest.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] As neutrons also have a magnetic moment, they are additionally scattered by any magnetic moments in a sample.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In the case of long range magnetic order, this leads to the appearance of new Bragg reflections.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In most simple cases, powder diffraction may be used to determine the size of the moments and their spatial orientation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] where the magnitude of the scattering vector *q* is in reciprocal lattice distance units, *N* is the number of atoms, *fi*(*q*) is the atomic scattering factor for atom *i* and scattering vector *q*, while *rij* is the distance between atom *i* and atom *j*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] One can also use this to predict the effect of nano-crystallite shape on detected diffraction peaks, even if in some directions the cluster is only one atom thick.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Semi-quantitative analysis of polycrystalline mixtures can be performed by using traditional single-peaks methods such as the Relative Intensity Ratio (RIR) or whole-pattern methods using Rietveld Refinement or PONKCS (Partial Or No Known Crystal Structures) method.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The use of each method depends on the knowledge on the analyzed system, given that, for instance, Rietveld refinement needs the solved crystal structure of each component of the mixture to be performed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In the last decades, multivariate analysis begun spreading as an alternative method for phase quantification.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The two types of cameras are known as the Laue and the Debye–Scherrer camera.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In order to ensure complete powder averaging, the capillary is usually spun around its axis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] For neutron diffraction vanadium cylinders are used as sample holders.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Vanadium has a negligible absorption and coherent scattering cross section for neutrons and is hence nearly invisible in a powder diffraction experiment.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Vanadium does however have a considerable incoherent scattering cross section which may cause problems for more sensitive techniques such as neutron inelastic scattering.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A later development in X-ray cameras is the Guinier camera.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] It is built around a *focusing* bent crystal monochromator.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The sample is usually placed in the focusing beam, e.g. as a dusting on a piece of sticky tape.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A cylindrical piece of film (or electronic multichannel detector) is put on the focusing circle, but the incident beam prevented from reaching the detector to prevent damage from its high intensity.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Cameras based on hybrid photon counting technology, such as the PILATUS detector, are widely used in applications where high data acquisition speeds and increased data quality are required.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Diffractometers can be operated both in transmission and reflection, but reflection is more common.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The powder sample is loaded in a small disc-like container and its surface carefully flattened.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The disc is put on one axis of the diffractometer and tilted by an angle *θ* while a detector (scintillation counter) rotates around it on an arm at twice this angle.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This configuration is known under the name Bragg–Brentano *θ*-2*θ*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Another configuration is the Bragg–Brentano *θ*-*θ* configuration in which the sample is stationary while the X-ray tube and the detector are rotated around it.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The angle formed between the X-ray source and the detector is 2*θ*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This configuration is most convenient for loose powders.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Diffractometer settings for different experiments can schematically be illustrated by a hemisphere, in which the powder sample resides in the origin.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The case of recording a pattern in the Bragg-Brentano *θ*-*θ* mode is shown in the figure, where **K**0 and **K** stand for the wave vectors of the incoming and diffracted beam that both make up the scattering plane.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Various other settings for texture or stress/strain measurements can also be visualized with this graphical approach.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Position-sensitive detectors (PSD) and area detectors, which allow collection from multiple angles at once, are becoming more popular on currently supplied instrumentation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Sources that produce a neutron beam of suitable intensity and speed for diffraction are only available at a small number of research reactors and spallation sources in the world.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Angle dispersive (fixed wavelength) instruments typically have a battery of individual detectors arranged in a cylindrical fashion around the sample holder, and can therefore collect scattered intensity simultaneously on a large 2θ range.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Time of flight instruments normally have a small range of banks at different scattering angles which collect data at varying resolutions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Laboratory X-ray diffraction equipment relies on the use of an X-ray tube, which is used to produce the X-rays.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The most commonly used laboratory X-ray tube uses a copper anode, but cobalt and molybdenum are also popular.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The wavelength in nm varies for each source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] According to the last re-examination of Hölzer et al.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In-house applications of X-ray diffraction has always been limited to the relatively few wavelengths shown in the table above.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The available choice was much needed because the combination of certain wavelengths and certain elements present in a sample can lead to strong fluorescence which increases the background in the diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] A notorious example is the presence of iron in a sample when using copper radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In general elements just below the anode element in the periodic table need to be avoided.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Another limitation is that the intensity of traditional generators is relatively low, requiring lengthy exposure times and precluding any time dependent measurement.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The advent of synchrotron sources has drastically changed this picture and caused powder diffraction methods to enter a whole new phase of development.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Not only is there a much wider choice of wavelengths available, the high brilliance of the synchrotron radiation makes it possible to observe changes in the pattern during chemical reactions, temperature ramps, changes in pressure and the like.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The tunability of the wavelength also makes it possible to observe anomalous scattering effects when the wavelength is chosen close to the absorption edge of one of the elements of the sample.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Neutron diffraction has never been an in house technique because it requires the availability of an intense neutron beam only available at a nuclear reactor or spallation source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Typically the available neutron flux, and the weak interaction between neutrons and matter, require relative large samples.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Although it is possible to solve crystal structures from powder X-ray data alone, its single crystal analogue is a far more powerful technique for structure determination.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This is directly related to the fact that information is lost by the collapse of the 3D space onto a 1D axis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Nevertheless, powder X-ray diffraction is a powerful and useful technique in its own right.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] It is mostly used to characterize and identify *phases*, and to refine details of an already known structure, rather than solving unknown structures.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] By contrast growth and mounting of large single crystals is notoriously difficult.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In fact there are many materials for which, despite many attempts, it has not proven possible to obtain single crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Many materials are readily available with sufficient microcrystallinity for powder diffraction, or samples may be easily ground from larger crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] In the field of solid-state chemistry that often aims at synthesizing *new* materials, single crystals thereof are typically not immediately available.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Powder diffraction is therefore one of the most powerful methods to identify and characterize new materials in this field.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Particularly for neutron diffraction, which requires larger samples than X-ray diffraction due to a relatively weak scattering cross section, the ability to use large samples can be critical, although newer and more brilliant neutron sources are being built that may change this picture.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] Since all possible crystal orientations are measured simultaneously, collection times can be quite short even for small and weakly scattering samples.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] This is not merely convenient, but can be essential for samples which are unstable either inherently or under X-ray or neutron bombardment, or for time-resolved studies.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] For the latter it is desirable to have a strong radiation source.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/powder-diffraction] The advent of synchrotron radiation and modern neutron sources has therefore done much to revitalize the powder diffraction field because it is now possible to study temperature dependent changes, reaction kinetics and so forth by means of time-resolved powder diffraction.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice is the set of all vectors $\mathbf {G} _{m}$ , that are wavevectors **k** of plane waves in the Fourier series of a spatial function whose periodicity is the same as that of a direct lattice $\mathbf {R} _{n}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Each plane wave in this Fourier series has the same phase or phases that are differed by multiples of $2\pi$ , at each direct lattice point (so essentially same phase at all the direct lattice points).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice of a reciprocal lattice is equivalent to the original direct lattice, because the defining equations are symmetrical with respect to the vectors in real and reciprocal space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Mathematically, direct and reciprocal lattice vectors represent covariant and contravariant vectors, respectively.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The Brillouin zone is a Wigner–Seitz cell of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Reciprocal space (also called k-space) provides a way to visualize the results of the Fourier transform of a spatial function.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] It is similar in role to the frequency domain arising from the Fourier transform of a time dependent function; reciprocal space is a space over which the Fourier transform of a spatial function is represented at spatial frequencies or wavevectors of plane waves of the Fourier transform.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The domain of the spatial function itself is often referred to as spatial domain or real space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In physical applications, such as crystallography, both real and reciprocal space will often each be two or three dimensional.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Whereas the number of spatial dimensions of these two associated spaces will be the same, the spaces will differ in their quantity dimension, so that when the real space has the dimension length (**L**), its reciprocal space will have inverse length, so **L**−1 (the reciprocal of length).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Reciprocal space comes into play regarding waves, both classical and quantum mechanical.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] This complementary role of k and x leads to their visualization within complementary spaces (the real space and the reciprocal space).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The spatial periodicity of this wave is defined by its wavelength $\lambda$ , where $k\lambda =2\pi$ ; hence the corresponding wavenumber in reciprocal space will be $k=2\pi /\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] (The magnitude of a wavevector is called wavenumber.) The constant $\varphi$ is the phase of the wavefront (a plane of a constant phase) through the origin $\mathbf {r} =0$ at time t , and $\mathbf {e}$ is a unit normal vector to this wavefront.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The wavefronts with phases $\varphi +(2\pi )n$ , where n represents any integer, comprise a set of parallel planes, equally spaced by the wavelength $\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In general, a geometric lattice is an infinite, regular array of vertices (points) in space, which can be modelled vectorially as a Bravais lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Some lattices may be skew, which means that their primary lines may not necessarily be at right angles.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In reciprocal space, a reciprocal lattice is defined as the set of wavevectors $\mathbf {k}$ of plane waves in the Fourier series of any function $f(\mathbf {r} )$ whose periodicity is compatible with that of an initial direct lattice in real space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Equivalently, a wavevector is a vertex of the reciprocal lattice if it corresponds to a plane wave in real space whose phase at any given time is the same (actually differs by $(2\pi )n$ with an integer n ) at every direct lattice vertex.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Cycling through the indices in turn, the same method yields three wavevectors $\mathbf {b} _{j}$ with $\mathbf {a} _{i}\cdot \mathbf {b} _{j}=2\pi \,\delta _{ij}$ , where the Kronecker delta $\delta _{ij}$ equals one when $i=j$ and is zero otherwise.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The $\mathbf {b} _{j}$ comprise a set of three primitive wavevectors or three primitive translation vectors for the reciprocal lattice, each of whose vertices takes the form $\mathbf {G} =m_{1}\mathbf {b} _{1}+m_{2}\mathbf {b} _{2}+m_{3}\mathbf {b} _{3}$ , where the $m_{j}$ are integers.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice is also a Bravais lattice as it is formed by integer combinations of the primitive vectors, that are $\mathbf {b} _{1}$ , $\mathbf {b} _{2}$ , and $\mathbf {b} _{3}$ in this case.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The Brillouin zone is a primitive cell (more specifically a Wigner–Seitz cell) of the reciprocal lattice, which plays an important role in solid state physics due to Bloch's theorem.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In pure mathematics, the dual space of linear forms and the dual lattice provide more abstract generalizations of reciprocal space and the reciprocal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] where $\mathbb {Z}$ is the set of integers and $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ is a primitive translation vector or shortly primitive vector.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Each plane wave in the Fourier series has the same phase (actually can be differed by a multiple of $2\pi$ ) at all the lattice point $\mathbf {R} _{n}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] (There may be other form of $\mathbf {G} _{m}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Here $\mathbf {Q}$ represents a 90 degree rotation matrix, i.e. a *q*uarter turn.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The anti-clockwise rotation and the clockwise rotation can both be used to determine the reciprocal lattice: If $\mathbf {Q}$ is the anti-clockwise rotation and $\mathbf {Q'}$ is the clockwise rotation, $\mathbf {Q} \,\mathbf {v} =-\mathbf {Q'} \,\mathbf {v}$ for all vectors $\mathbf {v}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Notably, in a 3D space this 2D reciprocal lattice is an infinitely extended set of Bragg rods—described by Sung et al.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] This choice also satisfies the requirement of the reciprocal lattice $e^{i\mathbf {G} _{m}\cdot \mathbf {R} _{n}}=1$ mathematically derived above.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] This method appeals to the definition, and allows generalization to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The cross product formula dominates introductory materials on crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The above definition is called the "physics" definition, as the factor of $2\pi$ comes naturally from the study of periodic structures.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] and so on for the other primitive vectors.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The crystallographer's definition has the advantage that the definition of $\mathbf {b} _{1}$ is just the reciprocal magnitude of $\mathbf {a} _{1}$ in the direction of $\mathbf {a} _{2}\times \mathbf {a} _{3}$ , dropping the factor of $2\pi$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] This can simplify certain mathematical manipulations, and expresses reciprocal lattice dimensions in units of spatial frequency.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] It is a matter of taste which definition of the lattice is used, as long as the two are not mixed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Each lattice point $(hk\ell )$ in the reciprocal lattice corresponds to a set of lattice planes $(hk\ell )$ in the real space lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] (A lattice plane is a plane crossing lattice points.) The direction of the reciprocal lattice vector corresponds to the normal to the real space planes.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The magnitude of the reciprocal lattice vector $\mathbf {K} _{m}$ is given in reciprocal length and is equal to the reciprocal of the interplanar spacing of the real space planes.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The formula for n dimensions can be derived assuming an n -dimensional real vector space V with a basis $(\mathbf {a} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {a} _{n})$ and an inner product $g\colon V\times V\to \mathbf {R}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice vectors are uniquely determined by the formula $g(\mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {b} _{j})=2\pi \delta _{ij}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Here, $\omega \colon V^{n}\to \mathbf {R}$ is the volume form, $g^{-1}$ is the inverse of the vector space isomorphism ${\hat {g}}\colon V\to V^{*}$ defined by ${\hat {g}}(v)(w)=g(v,w)$ and $\lrcorner$ denotes the inner multiplication.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Reciprocal lattices for the cubic crystal system are as follows.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The simple cubic Bravais lattice, with cubic primitive cell of side a , has for its reciprocal a simple cubic lattice with a cubic primitive cell of side ${\textstyle {\frac {2\pi }{a}}}$ (or ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{a}}}$ in the crystallographer's definition).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The cubic lattice is therefore said to be self-dual, having the same symmetry in reciprocal space as in real space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice to an FCC lattice is the body-centered cubic (BCC) lattice, with a cube side of ${\textstyle {\frac {4\pi }{a}}}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Locate a primitive unit cell of the FCC; i.e., a unit cell with one lattice point.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Now take one of the vertices of the primitive unit cell as the origin.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Give the basis vectors of the real lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Then from the known formulae, you can calculate the basis vectors of the reciprocal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] These reciprocal lattice vectors of the FCC represent the basis vectors of a BCC real lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The basis vectors of a real BCC lattice and the reciprocal lattice of an FCC resemble each other in direction but not in magnitude.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The reciprocal lattice to a BCC lattice is the FCC lattice, with a cube side of ${\textstyle 4\pi /a}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The simple hexagonal lattice is therefore said to be self-dual, having the same symmetry in reciprocal space as in real space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] One path to the reciprocal lattice of an arbitrary collection of atoms comes from the idea of scattered waves in the Fraunhofer (long-distance or lens back-focal-plane) limit as a Huygens-style sum of amplitudes from all points of scattering (in this case from each individual atom).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Here **g** = **q**/(2π) is the scattering vector **q** in crystallographer units, *N* is the number of atoms, *f**j*[**g**] is the atomic scattering factor for atom *j* and scattering vector **g**, while **r***j* is the vector position of atom *j*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The Fourier phase depends on one's choice of coordinate origin.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] when there are *j* = 1,*m* atoms inside the unit cell whose fractional lattice indices are respectively {*u**j*, *v**j*, *w**j*}.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] To consider effects due to finite crystal size, of course, a shape convolution for each point or the equation above for a finite lattice must be used instead.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Whether the array of atoms is finite or infinite, one can also imagine an "intensity reciprocal lattice" I[**g**], which relates to the amplitude lattice F via the usual relation *I* = *F***F* where *F** is the complex conjugate of F.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Since Fourier transformation is reversible, of course, this act of conversion to intensity tosses out "all except 2nd moment" (i.e. the phase) information.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Here **r***jk* is the vector separation between atom *j* and atom *k*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] One can also use this to predict the effect of nano-crystallite shape, and subtle changes in beam orientation, on detected diffraction peaks even if in some directions the cluster is only one atom thick.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] On the down side, scattering calculations using the reciprocal lattice basically consider an incident plane wave.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Thus after a first look at reciprocal lattice (kinematic scattering) effects, beam broadening and multiple scattering (i.e. dynamical) effects may be important to consider as well.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] There are actually two versions in mathematics of the abstract dual lattice concept, for a given lattice *L* in a real vector space *V*, of finite dimension.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The first, which generalises directly the reciprocal lattice construction, uses Fourier analysis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] It may be stated simply in terms of Pontryagin duality.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The dual group *V*^ to *V* is again a real vector space, and its closed subgroup *L*^ dual to *L* turns out to be a lattice in *V*^.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Therefore, *L*^ is the natural candidate for *dual lattice*, in a different vector space (of the same dimension).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The other aspect is seen in the presence of a quadratic form *Q* on *V*; if it is non-degenerate it allows an identification of the dual space *V** of *V* with *V*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The relation of *V** to *V* is not intrinsic; it depends on a choice of Haar measure (volume element) on *V*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] But given an identification of the two, which is in any case well-defined up to a scalar, the presence of *Q* allows one to speak to the dual lattice to *L* while staying within *V*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In mathematics, the dual lattice of a given lattice *L* in an abelian locally compact topological group *G* is the subgroup *L*∗ of the dual group of *G* consisting of all continuous characters that are equal to one at each point of *L*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In discrete mathematics, a lattice is a locally discrete set of points described by all integral linear combinations of dim = *n* linearly independent vectors in **R***n*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] The dual lattice is then defined by all points in the linear span of the original lattice (typically all of **R***n*) with the property that an integer results from the inner product with all elements of the original lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] It follows that the dual of the dual lattice is the original lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] Furthermore, if we allow the matrix *B* to have columns as the linearly independent vectors that describe the lattice, then the matrix $A=B\left(B^{\mathsf {T}}B\right)^{-1}$ has columns of vectors that describe the dual lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/reciprocal-lattice] In quantum physics, reciprocal space is closely related to *momentum space* according to the proportionality $\mathbf {p} =\hbar \mathbf {k}$ , where $\mathbf {p}$ is the momentum vector and $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In condensed matter physics and crystallography, the **static structure factor** (or **structure factor** for short) is a mathematical description of how a material scatters incident radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The structure factor is a critical tool in the interpretation of scattering patterns (interference patterns) obtained in X-ray, electron and neutron diffraction experiments.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Confusingly, there are two different mathematical expressions in use, both called 'structure factor'.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] One is usually written $S(\mathbf {q} )$ ; it is more generally valid, and relates the observed diffracted intensity per atom to that produced by a single scattering unit.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The other is usually written F or $F_{hk\ell }$ and is only valid for systems with long-range positional order — crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] It is the modulus squared $|F_{hk\ell }|^{2}$ that gives the scattering intensity. $F_{hk\ell }$ is defined for a perfect crystal, and is used in crystallography, while $S(\mathbf {q} )$ is most useful for disordered systems.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For partially ordered systems such as crystalline polymers there is obviously overlap, and experts will switch from one expression to the other as needed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The static structure factor is measured without resolving the energy of scattered photons/electrons/neutrons.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Energy-resolved measurements yield the dynamic structure factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Consider the scattering of a beam of wavelength $\lambda$ by an assembly of N particles or atoms stationary at positions $\textstyle \mathbf {R} _{j},j=1,\,\ldots ,\,N$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Assume that the scattering is weak, so that the amplitude of the incident beam is constant throughout the sample volume (Born approximation), and absorption, refraction and multiple scattering can be neglected (kinematic diffraction).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The direction of any scattered wave is defined by its scattering vector $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This vector is $\mathbf {q} =\mathbf {k_{s}} -\mathbf {k_{o}}$ , where $\mathbf {k_{s}}$ and $\mathbf {k_{o}}$ ( $|\mathbf {k_{s}} |=|\mathbf {k_{0}} |=2\pi /\lambda$ ) are the scattered and incident beam wavevectors, and $\theta$ is the angle between them.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For an assembly of atoms, $f_{j}$ is the atomic form factor of the j -th atom.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Another useful simplification is if the material is isotropic, like a powder or a simple liquid.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] An alternative derivation gives good insight, but uses Fourier transforms and convolution.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] To be general, consider a scalar (real) quantity $\phi (\mathbf {r} )$ defined in a volume V ; this may correspond, for instance, to a mass or charge distribution or to the refractive index of an inhomogeneous medium.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] If the scalar function is integrable, we can write its Fourier transform as $\textstyle \psi (\mathbf {q} )=\int _{V}\phi (\mathbf {r} )\exp(-i\mathbf {q} \cdot \mathbf {r} )\,\mathrm {d} \mathbf {r}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In the Born approximation the amplitude of the scattered wave corresponding to the scattering vector $\mathbf {q}$ is proportional to the Fourier transform $\textstyle \psi (\mathbf {q} )$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] with $\textstyle \mathbf {R} _{j},j=1,\,\ldots ,\,N$ the particle positions as before.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This is clearly the same as Equation (**1**) with all particles identical, except that here f is shown explicitly as a function of $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In general, the particle positions are not fixed and the measurement takes place over a finite exposure time and with a macroscopic sample (much larger than the interparticle distance).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The experimentally accessible intensity is thus an averaged one $\textstyle \langle I(\mathbf {q} )\rangle$ ; we need not specify whether $\langle \cdot \rangle$ denotes a time or ensemble average.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In a crystal, the constitutive particles are arranged periodically, with translational symmetry forming a lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The crystal structure can be described as a Bravais lattice with a group of atoms, called the basis, placed at every lattice point; that is, [crystal structure] = [lattice] $\ast$ [basis].
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] If the lattice is infinite and completely regular, the system is a perfect crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For such a system, only a set of specific values for $\mathbf {q}$ can give scattering, and the scattering amplitude for all other values is zero.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This set of values forms a lattice, called the reciprocal lattice, which is the Fourier transform of the real-space crystal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The structure factor is then simply the squared modulus of the Fourier transform of the lattice, and shows the directions in which scattering can have non-zero intensity.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] At these values of $\mathbf {q}$ the wave from every lattice point is in phase.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The value of the structure factor is the same for all these reciprocal lattice points, and the intensity varies only due to changes in f with $\mathbf {q}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The units of the structure-factor amplitude depend on the incident radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For X-ray crystallography they are multiples of the unit of scattering by a single electron (2.82 $\times 10^{-15}$ m); for neutron scattering by atomic nuclei the unit of scattering length of $10^{-14}$ m is commonly used.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The above discussion uses the wave vectors $|\mathbf {k} |=2\pi /\lambda$ and $|\mathbf {q} |=4\pi \sin \theta /\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] However, crystallography often uses wave vectors $|\mathbf {s} |=1/\lambda$ and $|\mathbf {g} |=2\sin \theta /\lambda$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Therefore, when comparing equations from different sources, the factor $2\pi$ may appear and disappear, and care to maintain consistent quantities is required to get correct numerical results.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In crystallography, the basis and lattice are treated separately.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where the sum is over all atoms in the unit cell, $x_{j},y_{j},z_{j}$ are the positional coordinates of the j -th atom, and $f_{j}$ is the scattering factor of the j -th atom.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The coordinates $x_{j},y_{j},z_{j}$ have the directions and dimensions of the lattice vectors $\mathbf {a} ,\mathbf {b} ,\mathbf {c}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] $F_{hk\ell }$ is the vector sum of waves from all atoms within the unit cell.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] An atom at any lattice point has the reference phase angle zero for all $hk\ell$ since then $(hx_{j}+ky_{j}+\ell z_{j})$ is always an integer.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] A wave scattered from an atom at (1/2, 0, 0) will be in phase if h is even, out of phase if h is odd.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Again an alternative view using convolution can be helpful.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Since [crystal structure] = [lattice] $\ast$ [basis], ${\mathcal {F}}$ [crystal structure] = ${\mathcal {F}}$ [lattice] $\times {\mathcal {F}}$ [basis]; that is, scattering $\propto$ [reciprocal lattice] $\times$ [structure factor].
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The FCC lattice is a Bravais lattice, and its Fourier transform is a body-centered cubic lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The most intense diffraction peak from a material that crystallizes in the FCC structure is typically the (111).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Films of FCC materials like gold tend to grow in a (111) orientation with a triangular surface symmetry.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] A zero diffracted intensity for a group of diffracted beams (here, $h,k,\ell$ of mixed parity) is called a systematic absence.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The diamond cubic crystal structure occurs for example in diamond (carbon), tin, and most semiconductors.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] There are 8 atoms in the cubic unit cell.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] But comparing this to the FCC above, we see that it is simpler to describe the structure as FCC with a basis of two atoms at (0, 0, 0) and (1/4, 1/4, 1/4).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The zincblende structure is similar to the diamond structure except that it is a compound of two distinct interpenetrating fcc lattices, rather than all the same element.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Cesium chloride is a simple cubic crystal lattice with a basis of Cs at (0,0,0) and Cl at (1/2, 1/2, 1/2) (or the other way around, it makes no difference).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The reciprocal lattice is easily constructed in one dimension: for particles on a line with a period a , the reciprocal lattice is an infinite array of points with spacing $2\pi /a$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In two dimensions, there are only five Bravais lattices.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The corresponding reciprocal lattices have the same symmetry as the direct lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] 2-D lattices are excellent for demonstrating simple diffraction geometry on a flat screen, as below.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Equations (1)–(7) for structure factor $S(\mathbf {q} )$ apply with a scattering vector of limited dimensionality and a crystallographic structure factor can be defined in 2-D as $F_{hk}=\sum _{j=1}^{N}f_{j}\mathrm {e} ^{[-2\pi i(hx_{j}+ky_{j})]}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] However, recall that real 2-D crystals such as graphene exist in 3-D.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The reciprocal lattice of a 2-D hexagonal sheet that exists in 3-D space in the $xy$ plane is a hexagonal array of lines parallel to the z or $z^{*}$ axis that extend to $\pm \infty$ and intersect any plane of constant z in a hexagonal array of points.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The Figure shows the construction of one vector of a 2-D reciprocal lattice and its relation to a scattering experiment.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] A parallel beam, with wave vector $\mathbf {k} _{i}$ is incident on a square lattice of parameter a .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The scattered wave is detected at a certain angle, which defines the wave vector of the outgoing beam, $\mathbf {k} _{o}$ (under the assumption of elastic scattering, $|\mathbf {k} _{o}|=|\mathbf {k} _{i}|$ ).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] One can equally define the scattering vector $\mathbf {q} =\mathbf {k} _{o}-\mathbf {k} _{i}$ and construct the harmonic pattern $\exp(i\mathbf {q} \mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In the depicted example, the spacing of this pattern coincides to the distance between particle rows: $q=2\pi /a$ , so that contributions to the scattering from all particles are in phase (constructive interference).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Thus, the total signal in direction $\mathbf {k} _{o}$ is strong, and $\mathbf {q}$ belongs to the reciprocal lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] It is easily shown that this configuration fulfills Bragg's law.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Technically a perfect crystal must be infinite, so a finite size is an imperfection.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Real crystals always exhibit imperfections of their order besides their finite size, and these imperfections can have profound effects on the properties of the material.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] André Guinier proposed a widely employed distinction between imperfections that preserve the long-range order of the crystal that he called *disorder of the first kind* and those that destroy it called *disorder of the second kind*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] An example of the first is thermal vibration; an example of the second is some density of dislocations.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The generally applicable structure factor $S(\mathbf {q} )$ can be used to include the effect of any imperfection.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In crystallography, these effects are treated as separate from the structure factor $F_{hkl}$ , so separate factors for size or thermal effects are introduced into the expressions for scattered intensity, leaving the perfect crystal structure factor unchanged.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Therefore, a detailed description of these factors in crystallographic structure modeling and structure determination by diffraction is not appropriate in this article.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For $S(q)$ a finite crystal means that the sums in equations 1-7 are now over a finite N .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The effect is most easily demonstrated with a 1-D lattice of points.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This function is shown in the Figure for different values of N .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] When the scattering from every particle is in phase, which is when the scattering is at a reciprocal lattice point $q=2k\pi /a$ , the sum of the amplitudes must be $\propto N$ and so the maxima in intensity are $\propto N^{2}$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Taking the above expression for $S(q)$ and estimating the limit $S(q\to 0)$ using, for instance, L'Hôpital's rule) shows that $S(q=2k\pi /a)=N$ as seen in the Figure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] At the midpoint $S(q=(2k+1)\pi /a)=1/N$ (by direct evaluation) and the peak width decreases like $1/N$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In the large N limit, the peaks become infinitely sharp Dirac delta functions, the reciprocal lattice of the perfect 1-D lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In crystallography when $F_{hkl}$ is used, N is large, and the formal size effect on diffraction is taken as $\left[{\frac {\sin(Nqa/2)}{(qa/2)}}\right]^{2}$ , which is the same as the expression for $S(q)$ above near to the reciprocal lattice points, $q\approx 2k\pi /a$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Using convolution, we can describe the finite real crystal structure as [lattice] $\ast$ [basis] $\times$ rectangular function, where the rectangular function has a value 1 inside the crystal and 0 outside it.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Then ${\mathcal {F}}$ [crystal structure] = ${\mathcal {F}}$ [lattice] $\times {\mathcal {F}}$ [basis] $\ast {F}$ [rectangular function]; that is, scattering $\propto$ [reciprocal lattice] $\times$ [structure factor] $\ast$ [ sinc function].
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Thus the intensity, which is a delta function of position for the perfect crystal, becomes a ${\textstyle \operatorname {sinc} ^{2}}$ function around every point with a maximum $\propto N^{2}$ , a width $\propto 1/N$ , area $\propto N$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This model for disorder in a crystal starts with the structure factor of a perfect crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where the disorder is measured by the mean-square displacement of the positions $x_{j}$ from their positions in a perfect one-dimensional lattice: $a(j-(N-1)/2)$ , i.e., $x_{j}=a(j-(N-1)/2)+\delta x$ , where $\delta x$ is a small (much less than a ) random displacement.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For disorder of the first kind, each random displacement $\delta x$ is independent of the others, and with respect to a perfect lattice.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Thus the displacements $\delta x$ do not destroy the translational order of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This has the consequence that for infinite crystals ( $N\to \infty$ ) the structure factor still has delta-function Bragg peaks – the peak width still goes to zero as $N\to \infty$ , with this kind of disorder.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] However, it does reduce the amplitude of the peaks, and due to the factor of $q^{2}$ in the exponential factor, it reduces peaks at large q much more than peaks at small q .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The structure is simply reduced by a q and disorder dependent term because all disorder of the first-kind does is smear out the scattering planes, effectively reducing the form factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In three dimensions the effect is the same, the structure is again reduced by a multiplicative factor, and this factor is often called the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Note that the Debye–Waller factor is often ascribed to thermal motion, i.e., the $\delta x$ are due to thermal motion, but any random displacements about a perfect lattice, not just thermal ones, will contribute to the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] However, fluctuations that cause the correlations between pairs of atoms to decrease as their separation increases, causes the Bragg peaks in the structure factor of a crystal to broaden.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] To see how this works, we consider a one-dimensional toy model: a stack of plates with mean spacing a .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] The derivation follows that in chapter 9 of Guinier's textbook.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This model has been pioneered by and applied to a number of materials by Hosemann and collaborators over a number of years.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Guinier and they termed this disorder of the second kind, and Hosemann in particular referred to this imperfect crystalline ordering as paracrystalline ordering.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Disorder of the first kind is the source of the Debye–Waller factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] To start with we will consider, for simplicity an infinite crystal, i.e., $N\to \infty$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] We will consider a finite crystal with disorder of the second-type below.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For our infinite crystal, we want to consider pairs of lattice sites.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For large each plane of an infinite crystal, there are two neighbours m planes away, so the above double sum becomes a single sum over pairs of neighbours either side of an atom, at positions $-m$ and m lattice spacings away, times N .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where $p_{m}(\Delta x)$ is the probability density function for the separation $\Delta x$ of a pair of planes, m lattice spacings apart.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] and we also assume that the fluctuations between a plane and its neighbour, and between this neighbour and the next plane, are independent.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Then $p_{2}(\Delta x)$ is just the convolution of two $p_{1}(\Delta x)$ s, etc.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] i.e., the height of successive peaks drop off as the order of the peak (and so q ) squared.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Unlike finite-size effects that broaden peaks but do not decrease their height, disorder lowers peak heights.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Note that here we assuming that the disorder is relatively weak, so that we still have relatively well defined peaks.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] which is a Lorentzian or Cauchy function, of FWHM $q_{P}^{2}\sigma _{2}^{2}/a=4\pi ^{2}n^{2}(\sigma _{2}/a)^{2}/a$ , i.e., the FWHM increases as the square of the order of peak, and so as the square of the wave vector q at the peak.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Finally, the product of the peak height and the FWHM is constant and equals $4/a$ , in the $q\sigma _{2}\ll 1$ limit.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] For the first few peaks where n is not large, this is just the $\sigma _{2}/a\ll 1$ limit.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where the factor in parentheses comes from the fact the sum is over nearest-neighbour pairs ( $m=1$ ), next nearest-neighbours ( $m=2$ ), ... and for a crystal of N planes, there are $N-1$ pairs of nearest neighbours, $N-2$ pairs of next-nearest neighbours, etc.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In contrast with crystals, liquids have no long-range order (in particular, there is no regular lattice), so the structure factor does not exhibit sharp peaks.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] They do however show a certain degree of short-range order, depending on their density and on the strength of the interaction between particles.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Liquids are isotropic, so that, after the averaging operation in Equation (**4**), the structure factor only depends on the absolute magnitude of the scattering vector $q=\left|\mathbf {q} \right|$ .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Even for interacting particles, at high scattering vector the structure factor goes to 1.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This result follows from Equation (**10**), since $S(q)-1$ is the Fourier transform of the "regular" function $g(r)$ and thus goes to zero for high values of the argument q .
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This reasoning does not hold for a perfect crystal, where the distribution function exhibits infinitely sharp peaks.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In the hard sphere model, the particles are described as impenetrable spheres with radius R ; thus, their center-to-center distance $r\geq 2R$ and they experience no interaction beyond this distance.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] This model has an analytical solution in the Percus–Yevick approximation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Although highly simplified, it provides a good description for systems ranging from liquid metals to colloidal suspensions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In an illustration, the structure factor for a hard-sphere fluid is shown in the Figure, for volume fractions $\Phi$ from 1% to 40%.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] In polymer systems, the general definition (**4**) holds; the elementary constituents are now the monomers making up the chains.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] However, the structure factor being a measure of the correlation between particle positions, one can reasonably expect that this correlation will be different for monomers belonging to the same chain or to different chains.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] Let us assume that the volume V contains $N_{c}$ identical molecules, each composed of $N_{p}$ monomers, such that $N_{c}N_{p}=N$ ( $N_{p}$ is also known as the degree of polymerization).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where indices $\alpha ,\beta$ label the different molecules and $j,k$ the different monomers along each molecule.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] On the right-hand side we separated *intramolecular* ( $\alpha =\beta$ ) and *intermolecular* ( $\alpha \neq \beta$ ) terms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/structure-factor] where $S_{1}(q)$ is the single-chain structure factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography has been fundamental in the development of many scientific fields.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In its first decades of use, this method determined the size of atoms, the lengths and types of chemical bonds, and the atomic-scale differences between various materials, especially minerals and alloys.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The method has also revealed the structure and function of many biological molecules, including vitamins, drugs, proteins and nucleic acids such as DNA, as well as viruses.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography is still the primary method for characterizing the atomic structure of materials and in differentiating materials that appear similar in other experiments.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystal structures can also help explain unusual electronic or elastic properties of a material, shed light on chemical interactions and processes, or serve as the basis for designing pharmaceuticals against diseases.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Modern work involves a number of steps all of which are important.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The preliminary steps include preparing good quality samples, careful recording of the diffracted intensities, and processing of the data to remove artifacts.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A variety of different methods are then used to obtain an estimate of the atomic structure, generically called direct methods.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] With an initial estimate further computational techniques such as those involving difference maps are used to complete the structure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The final step is a numerical refinement of the atomic positions against the experimental data, sometimes assisted by *ab-initio* calculations.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In almost all cases new structures are deposited in databases available to the international community.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals, though long admired for their regularity and symmetry, were not investigated scientifically until the 17th century.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Johannes Kepler hypothesized in his work *Strena seu de Nive Sexangula* (A New Year's Gift of Hexagonal Snow) (1611) that the hexagonal symmetry of snowflake crystals was due to a regular packing of spherical water particles.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The Danish scientist Nicolas Steno (1669) pioneered experimental investigations of crystal symmetry.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Steno showed that the angles between the faces are the same in every exemplar of a particular type of crystal (law of constancy of interfacial angles).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] René Just Haüy (1784) discovered that every face of a crystal can be described by simple stacking patterns of blocks of the same shape and size (law of decrements).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Hence, William Hallowes Miller in 1839 was able to give each face a unique label of three small integers, the Miller indices which remain in use for identifying crystal faces.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Haüy's study led to the idea that crystals are a regular three-dimensional array (a Bravais lattice) of atoms and molecules; a single unit cell is repeated indefinitely along three principal directions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the 19th century, a complete catalog of the possible symmetries of a crystal was worked out by Johan Hessel, Auguste Bravais, Evgraf Fedorov, Arthur Schönflies and (belatedly) William Barlow (1894).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Barlow proposed several crystal structures in the 1880s that were validated later by X-ray crystallography; however, the available data were too scarce in the 1880s to accept his models as conclusive.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Wilhelm Röntgen discovered X-rays in 1895.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Physicists were uncertain of the nature of X-rays, but suspected that they were waves of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The Maxwell theory of electromagnetic radiation was well accepted, and experiments by Charles Glover Barkla showed that X-rays exhibited phenomena associated with electromagnetic waves, including transverse polarization and spectral lines akin to those observed in the visible wavelengths.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-rays are not only waves but also have particle properties causing Sommerfeld to coin the name Bremsstrahlung for the continuous spectra when they were formed when electrons bombarded a material.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Albert Einstein introduced the photon concept in 1905, but it was not broadly accepted until 1922, when Arthur Compton confirmed it by the scattering of X-rays from electrons.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The particle-like properties of X-rays, such as their ionization of gases, had prompted William Henry Bragg to argue in 1907 that X-rays were *not* electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Bragg's view proved unpopular and the observation of X-ray diffraction by Max von Laue in 1912 confirmed that X-rays are a form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The idea that crystals could be used as a diffraction grating for X-rays arose in 1912 in a conversation between Paul Peter Ewald and Max von Laue in the English Garden in Munich.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Ewald had proposed a resonator model of crystals for his thesis, but this model could not be validated using visible light, since the wavelength was much larger than the spacing between the resonators.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue realized that electromagnetic radiation of a shorter wavelength was needed, and suggested that X-rays might have a wavelength comparable to the unit-cell spacing in crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue worked with two technicians, Walter Friedrich and his assistant Paul Knipping, to shine a beam of X-rays through a copper sulfate crystal and record its diffraction on a photographic plate.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] After being developed, the plate showed a large number of well-defined spots arranged in a pattern of intersecting circles around the spot produced by the central beam.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The results were presented to the Bavarian Academy of Sciences and Humanities in June 1912 as "Interferenz-Erscheinungen bei Röntgenstrahlen" (Interference phenomena in X-rays).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Von Laue developed a law that connects the scattering angles and the size and orientation of the unit-cell spacings in the crystal, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1914.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] After Von Laue's pioneering research, the field developed rapidly, most notably by contributions from physicists William Lawrence Bragg and his father William Henry Bragg.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In 1912–1913, the younger Bragg developed Bragg's law, which connects the scattering with evenly spaced planes within a crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The Braggs, father and son, shared the 1915 Nobel Prize in Physics for their work in crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The earliest structures were generally simple; as computational and experimental methods improved over the next decades, it became feasible to deduce reliable atomic positions for more complicated arrangements of atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The earliest structures were simple inorganic crystals and minerals, but even these revealed fundamental laws of physics and chemistry.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The first atomic-resolution structure to be "solved" (i.e., determined) in 1914 was that of table salt.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The distribution of electrons in the table-salt structure showed that crystals are not necessarily composed of covalently bonded molecules, and proved the existence of ionic compounds.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of diamond was solved in the same year, proving the tetrahedral arrangement of its chemical bonds and showing that the length of C–C single bond was about 1.52 angstroms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Other early structures included copper, calcium fluoride (CaF2, also known as *fluorite*), calcite (CaCO3) and pyrite (FeS2) in 1914; spinel (MgAl2O4) in 1915; the rutile and anatase forms of titanium dioxide (TiO2) in 1916; pyrochroite (Mn(OH)2) and, by extension, brucite (Mg(OH)2) in 1919.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Also in 1919, sodium nitrate (NaNO3) and caesium dichloroiodate (CsICl2) were determined by Ralph Walter Graystone Wyckoff, and the wurtzite (hexagonal ZnS) structure was determined in 1920.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of graphite was solved in 1916 by the related method of powder diffraction, which was developed by Peter Debye and Paul Scherrer and, independently, by Albert Hull in 1917.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The structure of graphite was determined from single-crystal diffraction in 1924 by two groups independently.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Hull also used the powder method to determine the structures of various metals, such as iron and magnesium.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography has led to a better understanding of chemical bonds and non-covalent interactions.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Her conclusions were anticipated by William Henry Bragg, who published models of naphthalene and anthracene in 1921 based on other molecules, an early form of molecular replacement.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The first structure of an organic compound, hexamethylenetetramine, was solved in 1923.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This was rapidly followed by several studies of different long-chain fatty acids, which are an important component of biological membranes.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the 1930s, the structures of much larger molecules with two-dimensional complexity began to be solved.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A significant advance was the structure of phthalocyanine, a large planar molecule that is closely related to porphyrin molecules important in biology, such as heme, corrin and chlorophyll.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the 1920s, Victor Moritz Goldschmidt and later Linus Pauling developed rules for eliminating chemically unlikely structures and for determining the relative sizes of atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] These rules led to the structure of brookite (1928) and an understanding of the relative stability of the rutile, brookite and anatase forms of titanium dioxide.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography—or, strictly speaking, an inelastic Compton scattering experiment—has also provided evidence for the partly covalent character of hydrogen bonds.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the field of organometallic chemistry, the X-ray structure of ferrocene initiated scientific studies of sandwich compounds, while that of Zeise's salt stimulated research into "back bonding" and metal-pi complexes.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Finally, X-ray crystallography had a pioneering role in the development of supramolecular chemistry, particularly in clarifying the structures of the crown ethers and the principles of host–guest chemistry.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Many complicated inorganic and organometallic systems have been analyzed using single-crystal methods, such as fullerenes, metalloporphyrins, and other complicated compounds.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Single-crystal diffraction is also used in the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The Cambridge Structural Database contains over 1,000,000 structures as of June 2019; most of these structures were determined by X-ray crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The application of X-ray crystallography to mineralogy began with the structure of garnet, which was determined in 1924 by Menzer.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A systematic X-ray crystallographic study of the silicates was undertaken in the 1920s.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This study showed that, as the Si/O ratio is altered, the silicate crystals exhibit significant changes in their atomic arrangements.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Machatschki extended these insights to minerals in which aluminium substitutes for the silicon atoms of the silicates.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The first application of X-ray crystallography to metallurgy also occurred in the mid-1920s.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Most notably, Linus Pauling's structure of the alloy Mg2Sn led to his theory of the stability and structure of complex ionic crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] On October 17, 2012, the Curiosity rover on the planet Mars at "Rocknest" performed the first X-ray diffraction analysis of Martian soil.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The results from the rover's CheMin analyzer revealed the presence of several minerals, including feldspar, pyroxenes and olivine, and suggested that the Martian soil in the sample was similar to the "weathered basaltic soils" of Hawaiian volcanoes.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography of biological molecules took off with Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin, who solved the structures of cholesterol (1937), penicillin (1946) and vitamin B12 (1956), for which she was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1964.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In 1969, she succeeded in solving the structure of insulin, on which she worked for over thirty years.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystal structures of proteins (which are irregular and hundreds of times larger than cholesterol) began to be solved in the late 1950s, beginning with the structure of sperm whale myoglobin by Sir John Cowdery Kendrew, for which he shared the Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Max Perutz in 1962.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Since that success, 190,000 X-ray crystal structures of proteins, nucleic acids and other biological molecules have been determined.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The nearest competing method in number of structures analyzed is nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy, which has resolved less than one tenth as many.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystallography can solve structures of arbitrarily large molecules, whereas solution-state NMR is restricted to relatively small ones (less than 70 kDa).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] X-ray crystallography is used routinely to determine how a pharmaceutical drug interacts with its protein target and what changes might improve it.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] However, intrinsic membrane proteins remain challenging to crystallize because they require detergents or other denaturants to solubilize them in isolation, and such detergents often interfere with crystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Membrane proteins are a large component of the genome, and include many proteins of great physiological importance, such as ion channels and receptors.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Helium cryogenics are used to reduce radiation damage in protein crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Two limiting cases of X-ray crystallography—"small-molecule" (which includes continuous inorganic solids) and "macromolecular" crystallography—are often used.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Small-molecule crystallography typically involves crystals with fewer than 100 atoms in their asymmetric unit; such crystal structures are usually so well resolved that the atoms can be discerned as isolated "blobs" of electron density.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In contrast, macromolecular crystallography often involves tens of thousands of atoms in the unit cell.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Such crystal structures are generally less well-resolved; the atoms and chemical bonds appear as tubes of electron density, rather than as isolated atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In general, small molecules are also easier to crystallize than macromolecules; however, X-ray crystallography has proven possible even for viruses and proteins with hundreds of thousands of atoms, through improved crystallographic imaging and technology.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The technique of single-crystal X-ray crystallography has three basic steps.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The first—and often most difficult—step is to obtain an adequate crystal of the material under study.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The crystal should be sufficiently large (typically larger than 0.1 mm in all dimensions), pure in composition and regular in structure, with no significant internal imperfections such as cracks or twinning.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the second step, the crystal is placed in an intense beam of X-rays, usually of a single wavelength (*monochromatic X-rays*), producing the regular pattern of reflections.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The angles and intensities of diffracted X-rays are measured, with each compound having a unique diffraction pattern.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] As the crystal is gradually rotated, previous reflections disappear and new ones appear; the intensity of every spot is recorded at every orientation of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Multiple data sets may have to be collected, with each set covering slightly more than half a full rotation of the crystal and typically containing tens of thousands of reflections.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the third step, these data are combined computationally with complementary chemical information to produce and refine a model of the arrangement of atoms within the crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The final, refined model of the atomic arrangement—now called a *crystal structure*—is usually stored in a public database.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Although crystallography can be used to characterize the disorder in an impure or irregular crystal, crystallography generally requires a pure crystal of high regularity to solve the structure of a complicated arrangement of atoms.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Pure, regular crystals can sometimes be obtained from natural or synthetic materials, such as samples of metals, minerals or other macroscopic materials.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The regularity of such crystals can sometimes be improved with macromolecular crystal annealing and other methods.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] However, in many cases, obtaining a diffraction-quality crystal is the chief barrier to solving its atomic-resolution structure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Small-molecule and macromolecular crystallography differ in the range of possible techniques used to produce diffraction-quality crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Small molecules generally have few degrees of conformational freedom, and may be crystallized by a wide range of methods, such as chemical vapor deposition and recrystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] By contrast, macromolecules generally have many degrees of freedom and their crystallization must be carried out so as to maintain a stable structure.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For example, proteins and larger RNA molecules cannot be crystallized if their tertiary structure has been unfolded; therefore, the range of crystallization conditions is restricted to solution conditions in which such molecules remain folded.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Protein crystals are almost always grown in solution.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The most common approach is to lower the solubility of its component molecules very gradually; if this is done too quickly, the molecules will precipitate from solution, forming a useless dust or amorphous gel on the bottom of the container.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystal growth in solution is characterized by two steps: *nucleation* of a microscopic crystallite (possibly having only 100 molecules), followed by *growth* of that crystallite, ideally to a diffraction-quality crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The solution conditions that favor the first step (nucleation) are not always the same conditions that favor the second step (subsequent growth).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The solution conditions should *disfavor* the first step (nucleation) but *favor* the second (growth), so that only one large crystal forms per droplet.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] If nucleation is favored too much, a shower of small crystallites will form in the droplet, rather than one large crystal; if favored too little, no crystal will form whatsoever.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Other approaches involve crystallizing proteins under oil, where aqueous protein solutions are dispensed under liquid oil, and water evaporates through the layer of oil.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Different oils have different evaporation permeabilities, therefore yielding changes in concentration rates from different percipient/protein mixture.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It is difficult to predict good conditions for nucleation or growth of well-ordered crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In practice, favorable conditions are identified by *screening*; a very large batch of the molecules is prepared, and a wide variety of crystallization solutions are tested.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Hundreds, even thousands, of solution conditions are generally tried before finding the successful one.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It is also common to try several temperatures for encouraging crystallization, or to gradually lower the temperature so that the solution becomes supersaturated.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] These methods require large amounts of the target molecule, as they use high concentration of the molecule(s) to be crystallized.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Due to the difficulty in obtaining such large quantities (milligrams) of crystallization-grade protein, robots have been developed that are capable of accurately dispensing crystallization trial drops that are in the order of 100 nanoliters in volume.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This means that 10-fold less protein is used per experiment when compared to crystallization trials set up by hand (in the order of 1 microliter).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Several factors are known to inhibit crystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The growing crystals are generally held at a constant temperature and protected from shocks or vibrations that might disturb their crystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Impurities in the molecules or in the crystallization solutions are often inimical to crystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Conformational flexibility in the molecule also tends to make crystallization less likely, due to entropy.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Molecules that tend to self-assemble into regular helices are often unwilling to assemble into crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals can be marred by twinning, which can occur when a unit cell can pack equally favorably in multiple orientations; although recent advances in computational methods may allow solving the structure of some twinned crystals.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Having failed to crystallize a target molecule, a crystallographer may try again with a slightly modified version of the molecule; even small changes in molecular properties can lead to large differences in crystallization behavior.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For proteins, impurities have been shown to sometimes enhance and sometimes disrupt crystal growth.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Oscillation with audible sound sometimes works.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] These issues may be related to the phase separation characteristic of protein crystalation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The crystal is mounted for measurements so that it may be held in the X-ray beam and rotated.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In the past, crystals were loaded into glass capillaries with the crystallization solution (the mother liquor).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Crystals of small molecules are typically attached with oil or glue to a glass fiber or a loop, which is made of nylon or plastic and attached to a solid rod.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Protein crystals are scooped up by a loop, then flash-frozen with liquid nitrogen.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This freezing reduces the radiation damage of the X-rays, as well as thermal motion (the Debye-Waller effect).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] However, untreated protein crystals often crack if flash-frozen; therefore, they are generally pre-soaked in a cryoprotectant solution before freezing.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This pre-soak may itself cause the crystal to crack, ruining it for crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Generally, successful cryo-conditions are identified by trial and error.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The capillary or loop is mounted on a goniometer, which allows it to be positioned accurately within the X-ray beam and rotated.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Since both the crystal and the beam are often very small, the crystal must be centered within the beam to within ~25 micrometers accuracy, which is aided by a camera focused on the crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The most common type of goniometer is the "kappa goniometer", which offers three angles of rotation: the ω angle, which rotates about an axis perpendicular to the beam; the κ angle, about an axis at ~50° to the ω axis; and, finally, the φ angle about the loop/capillary axis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] When the κ angle is zero, the ω and φ axes are aligned.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The κ rotation allows for convenient mounting of the crystal, since the arm in which the crystal is mounted may be swung out towards the crystallographer.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The oscillations carried out during data collection (mentioned below) involve the ω axis only.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] An older type of goniometer is the four-circle goniometer, and its relatives such as the six-circle goniometer.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The relative intensities of the reflections provides information to determine the arrangement of molecules within the crystal in atomic detail.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The intensities of these reflections may be recorded with photographic film, an area detector (such as a pixel detector) or with a charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The peaks at small angles correspond to low-resolution data, whereas those at high angles represent high-resolution data; thus, an upper limit on the eventual resolution of the structure can be determined from the first few images.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Some measures of diffraction quality can be determined at this point, such as the mosaicity of the crystal and its overall disorder, as observed in the peak widths.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Some pathologies of the crystal that would render it unfit for solving the structure can also be diagnosed quickly at this point.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] One set of spots is insufficient to reconstruct the whole crystal; it represents only a small slice of the full three dimensional set.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] To collect all the necessary information, the crystal must be rotated step-by-step through 180°, with an image recorded at every step; actually, slightly more than 180° is required to cover reciprocal space, due to the curvature of the Ewald sphere.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] However, if the crystal has a higher symmetry, a smaller angular range such as 90° or 45° may be recorded.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The rotation axis should be changed at least once, to avoid developing a "blind spot" in reciprocal space close to the rotation axis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It is customary to rock the crystal slightly (by 0.5–2°) to catch a broader region of reciprocal space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Multiple data sets may be necessary for certain phasing methods.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For example, multi-wavelength anomalous dispersion phasing requires that the scattering be recorded at least three (and usually four, for redundancy) wavelengths of the incoming X-ray radiation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A single crystal may degrade too much during the collection of one data set, owing to radiation damage; in such cases, data sets on multiple crystals must be taken.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The recorded series of two-dimensional diffraction patterns, each corresponding to a different crystal orientation, is converted into a three-dimensional set.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Data processing begins with *indexing* the reflections.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This means identifying the dimensions of the unit cell and which image peak corresponds to which position in reciprocal space.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A byproduct of indexing is to determine the symmetry of the crystal, i.e., its *space group*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Some space groups can be eliminated from the beginning.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For example, reflection symmetries cannot be observed in chiral molecules; thus, only 65 space groups of 230 possible are allowed for protein molecules which are almost always chiral.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Indexing is generally accomplished using an *autoindexing* routine.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Having assigned symmetry, the data is then *integrated*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A full data set may consist of hundreds of separate images taken at different orientations of the crystal.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] These have to be merged and scaled using peaks that appear in two or more images (*merging*) and scaling so there is a consistent intensity scale.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Optimizing the intensity scale is critical because the relative intensity of the peaks is the key information from which the structure is determined.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The repetitive technique of crystallographic data collection and the often high symmetry of crystalline materials cause the diffractometer to record many symmetry-equivalent reflections multiple times.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This allows calculating the symmetry-related R-factor, a reliability index based upon how similar are the measured intensities of symmetry-equivalent reflections, thus assessing the quality of the data.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The intensity of each diffraction 'spot' is proportional to the modulus squared of the structure factor.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The structure factor is a complex number containing information relating to both the amplitude and phase of a wave.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In order to obtain an interpretable *electron density map*, both amplitude and phase must be known (an electron density map allows a crystallographer to build a starting model of the molecule).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The phase cannot be directly recorded during a diffraction experiment: this is known as the phase problem.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Having obtained initial phases, an initial model can be built.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The atomic positions in the model and their respective Debye-Waller factors (or **B**-factors, accounting for the thermal motion of the atom) can be refined to fit the observed diffraction data, ideally yielding a better set of phases.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A new model can then be fit to the new electron density map and successive rounds of refinement are carried out.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This iterative process continues until the correlation between the diffraction data and the model is maximized.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A similar quality criterion is *R*free, which is calculated from a subset (~10%) of reflections that were not included in the structure refinement.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Both *R* factors depend on the resolution of the data.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] As a rule of thumb, *R*free should be approximately the resolution in angstroms divided by 10; thus, a data-set with 2 Å resolution should yield a final *R*free ~ 0.2.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Chemical bonding features such as stereochemistry, hydrogen bonding and distribution of bond lengths and angles are complementary measures of the model quality.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In iterative model building, it is common to encounter phase bias or model bias: because phase estimations come from the model, each round of calculated map tends to show density wherever the model has density, regardless of whether there truly is a density.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] This problem can be mitigated by maximum-likelihood weighting and checking using *omit maps*.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It may not be possible to observe every atom in the asymmetric unit.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In many cases, crystallographic disorder smears the electron density map.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Weakly scattering atoms such as hydrogen are routinely invisible.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It is also possible for a single atom to appear multiple times in an electron density map, e.g., if a protein sidechain has multiple (<4) allowed conformations.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In still other cases, the crystallographer may detect that the covalent structure deduced for the molecule was incorrect, or changed.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For example, proteins may be cleaved or undergo post-translational modifications that were not detected prior to the crystallization.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A common challenge in refinement of crystal structures results from crystallographic disorder.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Disorder can take many forms but in general involves the coexistence of two or more species or conformations.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Failure to recognize disorder results in flawed interpretation.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Pitfalls from improper modeling of disorder are illustrated by the discounted hypothesis of bond stretch isomerism.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Disorder is modelled with respect to the relative population of the components, often only two, and their identity.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In structures of large molecules and ions, solvent and counterions are often disordered.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] The use of computational methods for the powder X-ray diffraction data analysis is now generalized.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It typically compares the experimental data to the simulated diffractogram of a model structure, taking into account the instrumental parameters, and refines the structural or microstructural parameters of the model using least squares based minimization algorithm.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Most of these tools also allow Le Bail refinement (also referred to as profile matching), that is, refinement of the cell parameters based on the Bragg peaks positions and peak profiles, without taking into account the crystallographic structure by itself.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] More recent tools allow the refinement of both structural and microstructural data, such as the FAULTS program included in the FullProf Suite, which allows the refinement of structures with planar defects (e.g. stacking faults, twinnings, intergrowths).
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Many structures obtained in private commercial ventures to crystallize medicinally relevant proteins are not deposited in public crystallographic databases.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] A number of women were pioneers in X-ray crystallography at a time when they were excluded from most other branches of physical science.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Kathleen Lonsdale was a research student of William Henry Bragg, who had 11 women research students out of a total of 18.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] She is known for both her experimental and theoretical work.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Lonsdale joined his crystallography research team at the Royal Institution in London in 1923, and after getting married and having children, went back to work with Bragg as a researcher.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Lonsdale always advocated greater participation of women in science and said in 1970: "Any country that wants to make full use of all its potential scientists and technologists could do so, but it must not expect to get the women quite so simply as it gets the men. ...
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] It is utopian, then, to suggest that any country that really wants married women to return to a scientific career, when her children no longer need her physical presence, should make special arrangements to encourage her to do so?".
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] During this period, Lonsdale began a collaboration with William T.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Astbury on a set of 230 space group tables which was published in 1924 and became an essential tool for crystallographers.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] In 1932 Dorothy Hodgkin joined the laboratory of the physicist John Desmond Bernal, who was a former student of Bragg, in Cambridge, UK.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] She and Bernal took the first X-ray photographs of crystalline proteins.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Hodgkin also played a role in the foundation of the International Union of Crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] She was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1964 for her work using X-ray techniques to study the structures of penicillin, insulin and vitamin B12.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Her work on penicillin began in 1942 during the war and on vitamin B12 in 1948.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] While her group slowly grew, their predominant focus was on the X-ray analysis of natural products.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] She is the only British woman ever to have won a Nobel Prize in a science subject.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Rosalind Franklin worked on the X-ray photography of a DNA fibre that proved key to James Watson and Francis Crick's discovery of the double helix, for which they both won the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1962.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Watson revealed in his autobiographic account of the discovery of the structure of DNA, *The Double Helix*, that he had used Franklin's X-ray photograph without her permission.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Franklin died of cancer in her 30s, before Watson received the Nobel Prize.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Franklin also carried out important structural studies of carbon in coal and graphite, and of plant and animal viruses.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Isabella Karle of the United States Naval Research Laboratory developed an experimental approach to the mathematical theory of crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Her work improved the speed and accuracy of chemical and biomedical analysis.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Yet only her husband Jerome shared the 1985 Nobel Prize in Chemistry with Herbert Hauptman, "for outstanding achievements in the development of direct methods for the determination of crystal structures".
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Other prize-giving bodies have showered Isabella with awards in her own right.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Women have written many textbooks and research papers in the field of X-ray crystallography.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] For many years Lonsdale edited the *International Tables for Crystallography*, which provide information on crystal lattices, symmetry, and space groups, as well as mathematical, physical and chemical data on structures.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Olga Kennard of the University of Cambridge, founded and ran the Cambridge Crystallographic Data Centre, an internationally recognized source of structural data on small molecules, from 1965 until 1997.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Jenny Pickworth Glusker, a British scientist, co-authored *Crystal Structure Analysis: A Primer*, first published in 1971 and as of 2010 in its third edition.
[src:x-ray-diffraction/x-ray-crystallography] Eleanor Dodson, an Australian-born biologist, who began as Dorothy Hodgkin's technician, was the main instigator behind CCP4, the collaborative computing project that currently shares more than 250 software tools with protein crystallographers worldwide.
